    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "The way file system limits work, is that we tell the OS to raise the limits for us. So we say e.g. \"raise the ulimit to N\", and the OS says \"Ok, limit is now N\". \r\nHowever, the OS also has filesystems, and in this case I guess it's a particular mount which interacts with the AWS EFS. And _that_ particular filesystem does not support N. So basically, the OS is fine with `N`, and doesn't give any error, but then later on, the filesystem complains that it cannot support N open filehandles. \r\n\r\nUsing the libraries availalbe, we can't really handle this. The way to work around it is to `DatabaseHandles` in the toml config to limit this. \r\n```\r\n[Eth]\r\nDatabaseHandles = 32000\r\n```",
